Explain short circuiting:
Short circuiting in programming if and if / else statements, is the concept of
 the computer skipping over unnecessary evaluations. When using and / or operators,
  it exists when the outcome of the evaluation is determined before it finishes 
  evaluating. For example, when an and statement has two parts, and the first part 
  evaluates as false, a short circuit occurs when the computer skips evaluating the 
  second part, as no matter what it evaluates as, the first part of the and 
  statement will make the entire evaluation false. It is helpful in saving time for 
  the computer, since it would be fruitless to evaluate the second half after the 
  first half was proven false.
  